  "text": "Pregabalin was dissolved in sterilized saline and administered intraperitoneally (i.p.) at 2 mL/kg in the behavioral testing experiments (see below). p-IONX rats displaying mechanical allodynia (see below) following baseline behavioral testing were randomly placed into 5 different groups (n = 6/group) and received a single administration of pregabalin (.1, 1, 10, 100 mg/kg) or vehicle (saline) at postoperative day 7. This dose range of pregabalin was guided by our recent study showing that pregabalin at doses between 1 and 100 mg/kg was effective in dose-dependently attenuating orofacial electromyography activity and medullary release of glutamate evoked by noxious orofacial stimulation. [CITATION_1] The group of sham-operated rats (n = 6) received a single administration of 10 mg/kg pregabalin at postoperative day 7. Since 1 mg/kg was the minimum effective dose in the behavioral testing (see Results) during the neuronal recording experiments, pregabalin at a dose of 3 mg/ kg (or saline) was selected to be delivered after the baseline properties of each neuron were obtained (see below). The neuronal properties were also assessed at 30 and 60 minutes after drug administration, based on the time course reported in previous electrophysiological studies using systemically administered pregabalin.",
